Alright, let's delve into the intricate tapestry of Islam. Don't expect any saccharine pronouncements; this is about facts, presented with the stark clarity they deserve.

***

# Abrahamic Monotheistic Religion

This article focuses on the religion. For alternative meanings, consult [Islam (disambiguation)](/Islam_(disambiguation)).

## Islam (ٱلْإِسْلَام)

The [Kaaba](/Kaaba) at [Masjid al-Haram](/Masjid_al-Haram) in [Mecca](/Mecca), Saudi Arabia, stands as the [holiest Islamic site](/Holiest_sites_in_Islam).

*   **Classification:** [Abrahamic](/Abrahamic_religions), [Scripture](/Religious_text), [Quran](/Quran), Prophetic traditions: [Hadith](/Hadith) [1]
*   **Theology:** [Monotheistic](/Tawhid)
*   **Region:** [Middle East](/Middle_East), [North Africa](/North_Africa), [East Africa](/East_Africa), [West Africa](/West_Africa), [Central Asia](/Central_Asia), [South Asia](/South_Asia), [Southeast Asia](/Southeast_Asia), [Caucasus](/Caucasus), [Balkans](/Balkans), [Guianas](/Guianas) [2][3]
*   **Language:** [Quranic Arabic](/Classical_Arabic)
*   **Territory:** [Islamic world](/Islamic_world)
*   **Founder:** [Muhammad](/Muhammad) [4]
*   **Origin:** circa 610 CE, [Jabal al-Nour](/Jabal_al-Nour), [Mecca](/Mecca), [Hejaz](/Hejaz), Arabian Peninsula
*   **Separations:**
    *   [Ali-Illahism](/Ali-Illahism) [5]
    *   [Druze faith](/Druze_faith) [6]
    *   [Yazidism](/Yazidism) [7]
    *   [Yarsanism](/Yarsanism) [8]
    *   [Din-i Ilahi](/Din-i_Ilahi) [9]
    *   [Bábism](/B%C3%A1bism) [10]
    *   [Baháʼí Faith](/Bah%C3%A1%CA%BC%C3%AD_Faith) [11]
    *   [Ahmadi Religion](/Ahmadi_Religion) [12]
*   **Followers:** Estimated 2 billion [13] (individually referred to as [Muslims](/Muslims), collectively as the [Ummah](/Ummah))

***

**Islam** is an [Abrahamic](/Abrahamic_religions) [monotheistic](/Monotheistic) religion centered on the [Quran](/Quran), [15] and the teachings and practices of [Muhammad](/Muhammad). [16] Adherents, known as [Muslims](/Muslims), are the world's second-largest religious population, estimated at 2 billion worldwide, trailing only [Christianity](/Christianity). [13]

Muslims believe in a primordial, universal faith that was revealed through numerous prophets and messengers across history, including [Adam](/Adam_in_Islam), [Noah](/Noah_in_Islam), [Abraham](/Abraham_in_Islam), [Moses](/Moses_in_Islam), and [Jesus](/Jesus_in_Islam). They consider Islam to be the final and complete manifestation of this faith. The Quran is regarded as the verbatim word of [God](/God_in_Islam), an unaltered and final divine revelation. Alongside the Quran, Muslims acknowledge previous [revelations](/Islamic_holy_books), such as the [Tawrat](/Torah_in_Islam) (the [Torah](/Torah)), the [Zabur](/Zabur) ([Psalms](/Psalms)), and the [Injil](/Gospel_in_Islam) ([Gospel](/Gospel)). Muhammad is revered as the final prophet, the "[Seal of the Prophets](/Seal_of_the_Prophets)", through whom the divine message was perfected. The [Sunnah](/Sunnah), comprising Muhammad's teachings and normative example, meticulously documented in [hadith](/Hadith), serves as a fundamental guide for Muslim life.

The core tenets of Islam include the absolute oneness and uniqueness of God ([tawhid](/Tawhid)), and the belief in an afterlife ([akhirah](/Akhirah)) culminating in the [Last Judgment](/Judgement_Day_in_Islam). On this day, individuals will be judged for their deeds, with the righteous rewarded in [Jannah](/Jannah) (paradise) and the wicked punished in [Jahannam](/Jahannam) (hell). The [Five Pillars of Islam](/Five_Pillars_of_Islam) are the foundational, obligatory acts of worship: the declaration of faith ([shahada](/Shahada)), ritual prayers ([salah](/Salah)), almsgiving ([zakat](/Zakat)), fasting ([sawm](/Sawm)) during the month of [Ramadan](/Ramadan), and the pilgrimage ([hajj](/Hajj)) to [Mecca](/Mecca). [17][18] Islamic law, or [Sharia](/Sharia), encompasses virtually all aspects of life, from [banking and finance](/Islamic_banking_and_finance) and [welfare](/Zakat) to matters of [gender roles](/Gender_roles_in_Islam) and [environmental ethics](/Islamic_ethics). The two primary religious observances are [Eid al-Fitr](/Eid_al-Fitr) and [Eid al-Adha](/Eid_al-Adha). The three most sacred sites in Islam are [Masjid al-Haram](/Masjid_al-Haram) in Mecca, the [Prophet's Mosque](/Prophet%27s_Mosque) in [Medina](/Medina), and [al-Aqsa Mosque](/Al-Aqsa_Mosque) in [Jerusalem](/Jerusalem).

Islam originated in Mecca around 610 CE, marking the period when [Muhammad received his first revelation](/Muhammad%27s_first_revelation). By the time of his death, a significant portion of the [Arabian Peninsula](/Arabian_Peninsula) had embraced Islam. The early expansion of Muslim rule, under the [Rashidun Caliphate](/Rashidun_Caliphate) and later the [Umayyad Caliphate](/Umayyad_Caliphate), extended from the [Iberian Peninsula](/Al-Andalus) to the [Indus Valley](/Muslim_period_in_the_Indian_subcontinent). The [Islamic Golden Age](/Islamic_Golden_Age), particularly during the [Abbasid Caliphate](/Abbasid_Caliphate), witnessed a remarkable [scientific](/Science_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world), economic, and cultural efflorescence. The [spread of Islam](/Spread_of_Islam) occurred through various caliphates and states, facilitated by extensive trade, missionary activities ([dawah](/Dawah)), conquests, and imperial expansion.

The two principal [branches of Islam](/Islamic_schools_and_branches) are [Sunni Islam](/Sunni_Islam) (85–90%) [19] and [Shia Islam](/Shia_Islam) (10–15%). [20] While the [Shia–Sunni divide](/Shia%E2%80%93Sunni_divide) originated from disagreements over the [succession to Muhammad](/Succession_to_Muhammad), it has since evolved to encompass theological and juridical divergences. Sunni Muslims rely on the [Kutub al-Sittah](/Kutub_al-Sittah) as their canonical hadith collections, whereas Shia Muslims depend on [The Four Books](/The_Four_Books). Muslims constitute the majority population in 53 countries. [13] Indonesia hosts the largest Muslim population (12% of the global total), followed by South Asia (31%), the Middle East-North Africa region (20%), and sub-Saharan Africa (15%). Significant Muslim communities also exist in the [Americas](/Islam_in_the_Americas), China, and [Europe](/Islam_in_Europe). According to [Pew Research](/Pew_Research_Center), Islam is the world's fastest-growing major religion, primarily due to higher fertility rates and a younger demographic profile compared to other religious groups.

## Etymology

### Muslims § Etymology

In Arabic, **Islam** (إسلام, *al-Islām*) literally translates to "submission [to God]". [21][22][23] The term derives from the triliteral root س-ل-م (S-L-M), which encompasses concepts of submission, safety, and peace. [24] In a religious context, it signifies complete surrender to the will of [God](/God). A **Muslim** (مسلم, *muslim*) is defined as "one who submits to God," or "one who surrenders to God." [25][26] However, [Quranic studies](/Quranic_studies) scholar [Mohsen Goudarzi](/Mohsen_Goudarzi) posits that in the Quran, *dīn* means "[worship](/Worship)," *islām* means "[monotheism](/Monotheism)," and *muslim* means "monotheist." [27] The [Hadith of Gabriel](/Hadith_of_Gabriel) presents Islam as one component of a triad that includes [Iman](/Iman_(Islam)) (faith) and [Ihsan](/Ihsan) (excellence). [28][29]

Historically, Islam was referred to as Mohammedanism in the [English-speaking world](/English-speaking_world). This term has fallen into disuse and is often considered offensive, as it implies the centrality of a human figure rather than God in the faith. [30]

## Articles of Faith

### Aqidah and Iman (Islam)

The Islamic [creed](/Creed), or [aqidah](/Aqidah), is founded upon belief in six core articles: God, angels, divine revelation, prophets, the [Day of Resurrection](/Day_of_Resurrection), and divine predestination. [31]

#### God

The central concept in Islam is **Tawhid** (توحيد), the absolute oneness of God. This is understood as strict [monotheism](/Monotheism), though Islamic mystical traditions also incorporate [panentheistic](/Panentheism) elements. [32][33] God is considered incomparable and without multiplicity of persons, as in the [Christian Trinity](/Christian_Trinity). Associating multiplicity with God or attributing divine attributes to others is considered [idolatory](/Shirk) or *shirk*. Consequently, Muslims are not [iconodules](/Iconodule) and do not represent God in any form. God is known and referred to through numerous [names and attributes](/Names_of_God_in_Islam), the most prevalent being Ar-Rahmān (الرحمان, "The Entirely Merciful") and Ar-Rahīm (الرحيم, "The Especially Merciful"), which commence most chapters of the Quran. [34][35]

Islam teaches that God created the universe by His command, articulated in the phrase "[Be, and it is](/Be,_and_it_is)." [i][21] The ultimate [purpose of existence](/Purpose_of_life) is understood as the worship of God. [36] God is perceived as a personal entity, [21] with no intermediaries, such as clergy, required for divine communion. Awareness and consciousness of God are referred to as [Taqwa](/Taqwa). The term [Allah](/Allah) is unique, without plural or gender, and is used by Muslims and Arabic-speaking Christians and Jews to refer to God. In contrast, [ʾilāh](/ILAH) (إله) is a generic term for a deity. [37]

#### Angels

Angels (Arabic: ملك, *malak*) are described in the Quran [38] and hadith [39] as beings created to worship God and carry out specific duties, such as conveying divine [revelations](/Revelation), recording human actions, and receiving souls at the time of death. They are described as being created from 'light' (*nūr*) [40][41][42] or 'fire' (*nār*). [43][44][45][46] Islamic angels are often depicted in [anthropomorphic](/Anthropomorphism) forms combined with [supernatural](/Supernatural) characteristics, such as wings and immense size, and are adorned with celestial regalia. [47][48][49][50] Angels are understood to be free from bodily needs and desires, such as eating and drinking. [51] Prominent angels like [Gabriel](/Gabriel) (*Jibrīl*) and [Michael](/Michael_(archangel)) (*Mika'il*) are explicitly mentioned in the Quran. Angels feature prominently in narratives of the [Mi'raj](/Isra_and_Mi%27raj), Muhammad's celestial journey, where he encounters various angelic beings. [39] Angels also play a significant role in [Islamic eschatology](/Islamic_eschatology), [theology](/Kalam), and [philosophy](/Islamic_philosophy). [52]

#### Scriptures

The primary holy text in Islam is the [Quran](/Quran). Muslims believe its verses were revealed by God to Muhammad through the [archangel](/Archangel) Gabriel over a period spanning from 610 CE [53][54] to 632 CE, the year of Muhammad's passing. [55] During Muhammad's lifetime, these revelations were transcribed by [his companions](/Muhammad%27s_companions), though oral transmission through [memorization](/Hafiz_(Quran)) was also a crucial method. [56] The Quran comprises 114 chapters ([sūrah](/S%C5%ABrah)), containing a total of 6,236 verses ([āyāt](/Ayah)). The earlier Meccan chapters primarily address spiritual themes, while the later Medinan chapters focus on social and legal matters relevant to the nascent Muslim community. [21][57] The *hadith*, or accounts of Muhammad's life and teachings, are consulted by Muslim jurists to supplement and interpret the Quran. The study of Quranic exegesis is known as [tafsir](/Tafsir). [58][59] Beyond its religious significance, the Quran is widely acclaimed as a masterpiece of [Arabic literature](/Arabic_literature), [60][61] profoundly influencing both art and the Arabic language. [62]

Islam also posits that God has sent down revelations, termed [wahy](/Wahy), to various prophets throughout history. However, Muslims believe that certain previously revealed scriptures, such as the [Tawrat](/Tawrat) ([Torah](/Torah)) and the [Injil](/Injil) ([Gospel](/Gospel_in_Islam)), have been subject to distortion, either in textual content or interpretation. [63][64][53][65] The Quran, meaning 'Recitation,' is considered the final, verbatim, and uncorrupted word of God. [57][66][67][68]

#### Prophets

Prophets (Arabic: أنبياء, *anbiyāʾ*) are individuals chosen by God to convey His message. Those who also delivered a divine book are designated as "messengers" (*rasūl*). [70] Muslims believe prophets are strictly human, not divine. They are understood to have preached the same fundamental message of Islam—submission to God's will—to different communities throughout history, explaining the commonalities found across various religions. The Quran names many figures recognized as [prophets in Islam](/Prophets_in_Islam), including [Adam](/Adam_in_Islam), [Noah](/Noah_in_Islam), [Abraham](/Abraham_in_Islam), [Moses](/Moses_in_Islam), [David in Islam](/David_in_Islam), and [Jesus](/Jesus_in_Islam), among others. [21][71] Narratives concerning prophets beyond the Quranic accounts are compiled and explored in the [Qisas al-Anbiya](/Qisas_Al-Anbiya) (Stories of the Prophets).

Muhammad is believed by Muslims to be the final prophet, the "[Seal of the Prophets](/Seal_of_the_Prophets)," who delivered the complete message of Islam. [72][73] His life and example, known as the [Sunnah](/Sunnah) (literally, "trodden path"), serve as a model for Muslims, guiding their emulation of his moral conduct and providing crucial context for Quranic interpretation. [74][75][76][77] These examples are preserved in traditions known as [hadith](/Hadith), which document his words, actions, and character. [Hadith Qudsi](/Hadith_qudsi) represent a subcategory of hadith where God's verbatim words are quoted by Muhammad, distinct from the Quran. A hadith comprises a chain of narrators (*sanad*) and the actual text (*[matn](/Hadith_studies)*). Authenticity is assessed through various methodologies, with common classifications including "authentic" (*ṣaḥīḥ*), "good" (*ḥasan*), and "weak" (*ḍaʻīf*). [Hadith](/Hadith) collections like the [Kutub al-Sittah](/Kutub_al-Sittah) are highly regarded in [Sunni Islam](/Sunni_Islam), with [Sahih al-Bukhari](/Sahih_al-Bukhari) often considered the most authoritative source after the Quran. [The Four Books](/The_Four_Books) are similarly esteemed by [Shia Islam](/Shia_Islam). [78][79][80]

#### Resurrection and Judgment

Belief in the "Day of Resurrection," or [Yawm al-Qiyāmah](/Qiyamah) (يوم القيامة), is fundamental for Muslims. Its timing is decreed by God but remains unknown to humanity. The Quran, hadith, and scholarly commentaries describe the events and trials preceding and during this final day. The Quran specifically emphasizes [bodily resurrection](/Universal_resurrection), a departure from the pre-Islamic Arabian understanding of death. [81][82][83]

On Yawm al-Qiyāmah, all individuals will be judged by God based on their deeds. Those who have performed good deeds will be rewarded with entry into [Jannah](/Jannah) (paradise), while those who have committed evil will face punishment in [Jahannam](/Jahannam) (hell). [84] The Quran states in [Surat al-Zalzalah](/Surat_al-Zalzalah): "So whoever does an atom's weight of good will see it. And whoever does an atom's weight of evil will see it." The Quran enumerates various sins that can lead to condemnation in [hell](/Hell), but also affirms God's forgiveness for those who repent. Good deeds, such as charity, prayer, and compassion towards animals, [85] are believed to be rewarded with eternal bliss in paradise. Islamic conceptions of paradise describe it as a place of profound joy and blessings, with mystical traditions framing these delights within the context of ecstatic awareness of God. [86][87][88] Yawm al-Qiyāmah is also referred to in the Quran as Yawm ad-Dīn (يوم الدين, "Day of Judgment"); [ii] as-Sāʿah (الساعة, "the Last Hour"); [iii] and [al-Qāriʿah](/Al-Qaria) (القارعة, "The Clatterer"). [iv]

#### Divine Predestination

The concept of divine predestination in Islam ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): القضاء والقدر, *al-qadāʾ wa l-qadar*) asserts that all matters, both good and bad, are ordained by God. The term *al-qadar* signifies "power" and is derived from a root meaning "to measure" or "to calculate." [89][90][91][92] Muslims often express this belief by saying "In-sha-Allah" ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): إن شاء الله), meaning "if God wills," when discussing future events. [93]

## Acts of Worship

### Five Pillars of Islam and Ibadah

The five obligatory acts of worship, known as the "Pillars of Islam" (*Arkān al-Islām*), are the [Shahada](/Shahada) (declaration of faith), the five daily prayers, [Zakat](/Zakat) (almsgiving), fasting during [Ramadan](/Ramadan), and the [Hajj](/Hajj) pilgrimage. [94] Additionally, Muslims are encouraged to perform optional, supererogatory acts of devotion. [95]

#### Declaration of Faith

The [Shahada](/Shahada) [96] is the Islamic oath of allegiance, a declaration of faith. The full statement is: "ʾašhadu ʾal-lā ʾilāha ʾillā-llāhu wa ʾašhadu ʾanna muħammadan rasūlu-llāh" (أشهد أن لا إله إلا الله وأشهد أن محمداً رسول الله), meaning, "I testify that there is no [deity](/Deity) but [God](/God_in_Islam), and I testify that Muhammad is the messenger of God." [97] The simplicity of the creed is often highlighted, with the Shahada forming the foundation of the entire religion. Non-Muslims seeking to [convert to Islam](/Convert_to_Islam) must recite the Shahada in the presence of witnesses. [98][99]

#### Prayer

Prayer in Islam, known as [as-salah](/Salah) or *aṣ-ṣalāt* (الصلاة), is considered a direct communion with God. It involves a series of ritual units called [rakat](/Rakat), which include [bowing](/Ruku) and [prostrating](/Sujud) in devotion. The five daily prayers are obligatory. These prayers are performed in Arabic and oriented towards the [Kaaba](/Kaaba) in [Mecca](/Mecca), a direction known as the [Qibla](/Qibla). Ritual purity, achieved through a ritual washing called [Wudu](/Wudu) or a full body wash known as [Ghusl](/Ghusl), is a prerequisite for prayer. [100][101][102][103]

A [mosque](/Mosque) serves as a place of Muslim worship, referred to by its Arabic name, *masjid*. While primarily a site for prayer, mosques also function as vital social centers for the [Muslim community](/Ummah). For instance, the [Masjid an-Nabawi](/Al-Masjid_an-Nabawi) ("Prophetic Mosque") in [Medina](/Medina), [Saudi Arabia](/Saudi_Arabia), historically provided shelter for the impoverished. [Minarets](/Minaret) are distinctive towers from which the [Adhan](/Adhan), the call to prayer, is recited. [104][105][106]

#### Almsgiving

[Zakat](/Zakat) (زكاة, *zakāh*), or almsgiving, is a mandatory charitable contribution, typically 2.5% of accumulated wealth annually, paid by those who can afford it to aid the poor, debtors, captives, and those employed in its collection. [107] It functions as a system of [welfare](/Welfare_spending) within Muslim societies. [108] Zakat is viewed as a religious obligation, a trust from God's bounty owed to the needy, and an act of purifying one's surplus wealth. [109][110] The total annual contribution through zakat is estimated to be fifteen times greater than global humanitarian aid donations. [111] *Sadaqah* is a voluntary, highly encouraged form of charity, distinct from zakat. [112][113] A [Waqf](/Waqf) is a perpetual charitable endowment, often funding institutions like hospitals and schools. [114]

#### Fasting

Fasting in Islam, known as *ṣawm* (صوم), involves abstaining from food, drink, and other bodily consumptions, including [smoking](/Smoking_in_Islam), from dawn until sunset. [115] It is a duty for Muslims during the month of [Ramadan](/Ramadan). The purpose of fasting is to foster a sense of closeness to God through self-restraint and to cultivate empathy for the less fortunate. Other days, such as the [Day of Arafah](/Day_of_Arafah), are designated for optional fasting. [116]

#### Pilgrimage

The Islamic [pilgrimage](/Pilgrimage), known as *ḥajj* (حج), is a once-in-a-lifetime obligation for all Muslims who are able to perform it, occurring during the [Islamic month](/Islamic_calendar) of [Dhu al-Hijjah](/Dhu_al-Hijjah). The rituals largely commemorate the actions of the family of [Abraham](/Abraham_in_Islam). Pilgrims circumambulate the [Kaaba](/Kaaba) seven times, which Muslims believe Abraham built as a place of worship. They also walk seven times between the hills of [Safa and Marwa](/Safa_and_Marwa), reenacting the search for water by Abraham's wife, [Hagar](/Hagar), before Mecca became a settled community. [117][118][119] The Hajj also involves a day of prayer and reflection at [Mount Arafat](/Mount_Arafat) and the symbolic [stoning of the Devil](/Stoning_of_the_Devil). [120] Male pilgrims typically wear two simple, unstitched white garments called [ihram](/Ihram_clothing), signifying unity and equality among participants regardless of social status. [121][122] The optional [Umrah](/Umrah) pilgrimage can be performed at any time of the year. Other significant pilgrimage sites include [Medina](/Medina), the burial place of Muhammad, and [Jerusalem](/Jerusalem), a city central to many Islamic prophets and the site of [Al-Aqsa](/Al-Aqsa), which was once the direction of prayer before the Kaaba. [123][124]

## Other Acts of Worship

### Quran Recitation, Dua, and Dhikr

Muslims are encouraged to recite and memorize the Quran, or portions thereof, as acts of virtue. [Tajwid](/Tajwid) refers to the rules governing the proper [elocution](/Elocution) of the Quran. [125] Many Muslims complete the recitation of the entire Quran during [Ramadan](/Ramadan). [126] An individual who has memorized the entire Quran is known as a *hafiz* ("memorizer"), and hadith traditions suggest such individuals will be able to intercede for others on Judgment Day. [127]

Supplication to God, known as *duʿāʾ* (دعاء), has its own etiquette, which may include [raising hands](/Raising_hands_in_dua) in a gesture of pleading. [128]

The remembrance of God (*dhikr*, ذكر) involves the repetition of phrases that reference God. Common examples include *Tahmid* (الحمد لله, *al-Ḥamdu lillāh*), meaning "[praise be due to God](/Alhamdulillah)," recited during prayer or upon experiencing gratitude; *Tasbih*, glorifying God; and saying "[in the name of God](/Basmala)" (*basmalah*, بسملة) before commencing an activity, such as eating. [129]

## History

### Muhammad and the Beginning of Islam (570–632)

#### Muhammad and Muhammad in Islam

#### Timeline of Early Islamic History

#### Muhammad in Mecca, Early Social Changes Under Islam, First Islamic State

According to Islamic tradition, Muhammad was born in [Mecca](/Mecca) in 570 CE [570] and was orphaned in early childhood. He grew up as a merchant, earning the reputation of "[the trusted one](/Amin_(name))" (الامين, *al-Amīn*) and was often sought for his impartiality as an arbitrator. He later married his employer, the businesswoman [Khadija](/Khadija_bint_Khuwaylid). [130] In 610 CE, concerned by the moral decay and idolatry prevalent in Mecca, and seeking solitude for spiritual contemplation, Muhammad retreated to the [Cave of Hira](/Cave_of_Hira) on [Jabal al-Nour](/Jabal_al-Nour), a mountain near Mecca. It was during this retreat that he is said to have received the first revelation of the [Quran](/Quran) from the angel [Gabriel](/Gabriel). [53] This event, known as the "[Night of Power](/Night_of_Power)" (*Laylat al-Qadr*), is considered a pivotal moment in Islamic history. Over the subsequent 22 years, from the age of 40, Muhammad continued to receive divine revelations, establishing him as the last prophet, the "[seal of the prophets](/Seal_of_the_Prophets)." [63][64][131]

"Muhammad at the Ka'ba" from the [Siyer-i Nebi](/Siyer-i_Nebi). Muhammad's face is veiled (c. 1595).

During his time in Mecca, Muhammad began preaching, initially in private, then publicly, urging his listeners to abandon [polytheism](/Arab_polytheism) and worship the one God. Many early converts were from marginalized groups, including women, the poor, foreigners, and slaves, such as the first [muezzin](/Muezzin), [Bilal ibn Rabah al-Habashi](/Bilal_ibn_Rabah_al-Habashi). [133] The Meccan elite perceived Muhammad's message as a threat to their social hierarchy, as he challenged the established order and offered a different vision to the underprivileged, particularly given their economic reliance on the idol worship at the Kaaba. [134][135]

Following 12 years of persecution by the Meccans, Muhammad and his [companions](/Sahaba) undertook the [Hijra](/Hegira) ("emigration") in 622 CE to Yathrib, later renamed Medina. There, Muhammad established the [first Islamic state](/First_Islamic_state), uniting the Medinan converts ([Ansar](/Ansar_(Islam))) and the Meccan migrants ([Muhajirun](/Muhajirun)). The [Constitution of Medina](/Constitution_of_Medina) was established, outlining rights and responsibilities for the diverse communities within the city, including religious freedoms and autonomy in legal matters, alongside a commitment to mutual defense against external threats. [136] Muslim forces achieved victory at the [Battle of Badr](/Battle_of_Badr) in 624. Subsequent engagements included the inconclusive [Battle of Uhud](/Battle_of_Uhud) [137] and the [Battle of the Trench](/Battle_of_the_Trench) (March–April 627), where Medina successfully repelled an attempted siege. The [Treaty of Hudaybiyyah](/Treaty_of_Hudaybiyyah) was signed in 628, establishing a truce between Mecca and the Muslims, though it was later violated by Mecca. As more tribes converted to Islam, Meccan trade routes were disrupted by Muslim actions. [138][139] The [conquest of Mecca](/Conquest_of_Mecca) occurred in 629 with minimal bloodshed, and by Muhammad's death in 632 at the age of 62, he had unified the [tribes of Arabia](/Tribes_of_Arabia) into a singular religious and political entity. [53]

#### Early Islamic Period (632–750)

##### Succession to Muhammad and Early Muslim Conquests

##### Ghadir Khumm and Saqifa

##### Dome of the Rock in Jerusalem, built by Caliph [Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan](/Abd_al-Malik_ibn_Marwan), completed at the end of the [Second Fitna](/Second_Fitna).

Muhammad passed away in 632 CE. His immediate successors, known as [Caliphs](/Caliph)—[Abu Bakr](/Abu_Bakr), [Umar](/Umar), [Uthman ibn al-Affan](/Uthman_ibn_al-Affan), [Ali ibn Abi Talib](/Ali_ibn_Abi_Talib), and sometimes [Hasan ibn Ali](/Hasan_ibn_Ali)—are referred to in [Sunni Islam](/Sunni_Islam) as the *al-khulafāʾ ar-rāshidūn* ("Rightly Guided Caliphs"). [140][141] Following Muhammad's death, some tribes renounced Islam and rallied behind new prophets, but were subdued by Abu Bakr in the [Ridda wars](/Ridda_wars). [142][143][144][145][146] Local populations of Jews and indigenous Christians, who often faced persecution and heavy taxation as religious minorities, frequently facilitated Muslim expansion into [Persian](/Sassanid_Empire) and [Byzantine](/Byzantine) territories. [147] Uthman's election in 644 [was followed by his assassination](/Election_of_Uthman), leading to Ali's caliphate. The [First Fitna](/First_Fitna) (civil war) erupted when Muhammad's widow, [Aisha](/Aisha), led an army against Ali, seeking retribution for Uthman's death, but was defeated at the [Battle of the Camel](/Battle_of_the_Camel). Ali's attempt to depose the governor of Syria, [Mu'awiya](/Mu%27awiya), perceived as corrupt, led to conflict. Mu'awiya's rebellion culminated in his defeat at the [Battle of Siffin](/Battle_of_Siffin). Ali's decision to accept arbitration angered the [Kharijites](/Kharijites), an extremist faction who deemed him a sinner for not upholding divine judgment. The Kharijites were subsequently defeated at the [Battle of Nahrawan](/Battle_of_Nahrawan), but Ali was later assassinated by a Kharijite extremist. Ali's son, Hasan ibn Ali, was elected Caliph but abdicated to Mu'awiya under a peace treaty aimed at preventing further bloodshed, in exchange for Mu'awiya's pledge not to appoint a successor. [152] Mu'awiya established the [Umayyad dynasty](/Umayyad_dynasty) by designating his son [Yazid I](/Yazid_I) as his successor, triggering the [Second Fitna](/Second_Fitna). The killing of [Husayn ibn Ali](/Husayn_ibn_Ali), Ali's son, by Yazid's forces at the [Battle of Karbala](/Battle_of_Karbala) is an event commemorated annually by Shia Muslims. Sunni opposition, led by [Ibn al-Zubayr](/Ibn_al-Zubayr), challenged the dynastic succession, but was ultimately defeated at the [siege of Mecca](/Siege_of_Mecca_(692)). These leadership disputes were foundational to the [Sunni–Shia schism](/Shia%E2%80%93Sunni_divide), with Shia Muslims believing leadership should remain within Muhammad's family through Ali, known as the [Ahl al-Bayt](/Ahl_al-Bayt). [153][154]

The compilation of the Quran began during Abu Bakr's caliphate. Caliph [Umar ibn Abd al-Aziz](/Umar_ibn_Abd_al-Aziz) established a committee, [The Seven Fuqaha of Medina](/The_Seven_Fuqaha_of_Medina), [155][156] and [Malik ibn Anas](/Malik_ibn_Anas) authored one of the earliest texts on Islamic jurisprudence, the [Muwatta](/Muwatta_Imam_Malik), reflecting the consensus of these jurists. [157][158][159] The Kharijites, adhering to a strict binary of good and evil, declared any Muslim committing a major sin an unbeliever. This label has, in modern times, been applied to groups such as [ISIS](/ISIS). [160] Conversely, the [Murji'ah](/Murji%27ah) espoused the belief that judgment of an individual's piety rests solely with God, implying that wrongdoers might be misguided but not necessarily infidels. [161] This theological stance gained traction and became prevalent within mainstream Islamic beliefs. [162]

The Umayyad dynasty expanded its reach across the [Maghreb](/Maghreb), the [Iberian Peninsula](/Iberian_Peninsula), [Narbonnese Gaul](/Gallia_Narbonensis), and [Sindh](/Sindh). [163] The Umayyads faced challenges regarding legitimacy and relied heavily on their military patronage. [164] The *jizya*, a tax levied on non-Muslims, exempted them from military service, and the Umayyads resisted recognizing the conversions of non-Arabs to maintain revenue. [162] While the Rashidun Caliphate emphasized austerity, exemplified by Umar's requirement for official inventories of possessions, [165] the Umayyad penchant for luxury fostered dissent among the pious. [162] The Kharijites instigated the [Berber Revolt](/Berber_Revolt), leading to the establishment of the first independent Muslim states outside the Caliphate's direct control. The [Abbasid Revolution](/Abbasid_Revolution) saw the overthrow of the Umayyads by a coalition of non-Arab converts (*[Mawali](/Mawali)*), Arab clans marginalized by the Umayyad clan, and some Shia sympathizers, ushering in the more cosmopolitan Abbasid dynasty in 750. [166][167]

#### Classical Era (750–1258)

##### Hadith Studies and Islamic Philosophy

##### Islamic World Contributions to Medieval Europe and Turco-Persian Tradition

Al-Shafi'i codified a method for assessing the reliability of hadith. [168] During the early Abbasid period, scholars like [Muhammad al-Bukhari](/Muhammad_al-Bukhari) and [Muslim ibn al-Hajjaj](/Muslim_ibn_al-Hajjaj) compiled major [Sunni hadith collections](/Six_major_Hadith_collections), while figures such as [Al-Kulayni](/Muhammad_ibn_Ya%27qub_al-Kulayni) and [Ibn Babawayh](/Ibn_Babawayh) compiled significant Shia collections. The four major Sunni [Madhhabs](/Madhhab)—Hanafi, Hanbali, Maliki, and Shafi'i—were established based on the teachings of [Abū Ḥanīfa](/Ab%C5%AB_%E1%B8%A4an%C4%ABfa), [Ahmad ibn Hanbal](/Ahmad_ibn_Hanbal), Malik ibn Anas, and [al-Shafi'i](/Al-Shafi%27i), respectively. In contrast, [Ja'far al-Sadiq](/Ja%27far_al-Sadiq)'s teachings formed the basis of [Ja'fari jurisprudence](/Ja%27fari_jurisprudence). In the 9th century, [Al-Tabari](/Al-Tabari) completed the first comprehensive Quranic commentary, the [Tafsir al-Tabari](/Tafsir_al-Tabari), which became highly influential within Sunni Islam. Asceticism and a focus on spiritual purification, inspired by figures like [Hasan al-Basri](/Hasan_al-Basri), gained prominence, evolving into the mystical tradition known as *tasawwuf* or [Sufism](/Sufism). [169][170]

Theological debates, particularly concerning free will, were prominent during this era. Hasan al-Basri argued that while God possesses foreknowledge, human actions, both good and evil, stem from the misuse of free will and the influence of [Satan](/Iblis). [171][b] The [Muʿtazila](/Mu%CA%BFtazila), a rationalist philosophical school, championed the concept of human free will, originating with [Wasil ibn Ata](/Wasil_ibn_Ata). [173] Caliph [Mamun al Rashid](/Mamun_al_Rashid) adopted this as an official creed and attempted to enforce it, though unsuccessfully. [174] The traditionalist [Ahmad ibn Hanbal](/Ahmad_ibn_Hanbal) famously resisted the Muʿtazila doctrine that the Quran was [created rather than eternal](/Quranic_createdness), enduring torture and imprisonment for nearly thirty months. [175] However, other schools of speculative theology, such as [Maturidism](/Maturidi), founded by [Abu Mansur al-Maturidi](/Abu_Mansur_al-Maturidi), and [Ash'ari](/Ash%27ari), founded by [Al-Ash'ari](/Al-Ash%27ari), achieved wider acceptance. Philosophers like [Al-Farabi](/Al-Farabi), [Avicenna](/Avicenna), and [Averroes](/Averroes) attempted to reconcile Aristotelian thought with Islamic teachings, a pursuit paralleled by [scholasticism](/Scholasticism) in [Christianity](/Christianity_in_Europe) and the work of [Maimonides](/Maimonides) in Judaism. Conversely, figures like [Al-Ghazali](/Al-Ghazali) argued against such [syncretism](/Syncretism) and ultimately gained considerable influence. [176][177]

This period is often referred to as the "[Islamic Golden Age](/Islamic_Golden_Age)". [178][179][166][180][149] Islamic scientific contributions spanned diverse fields, including [medicine](/Medicine_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world), [mathematics](/Mathematics_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world), [astronomy](/Astronomy_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world), and [agriculture](/Arab_Agricultural_Revolution), as well as [physics](/Physics_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world), [economics](/History_of_Islamic_economics), [engineering](/List_of_inventions_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world), and [optics](/Ibn_al-Haytham). [181][182][183][184] [Avicenna](/Avicenna) was a pioneer in [experimental medicine](/Medical_research), [185][186] and his *The Canon of Medicine* served as a foundational medical text for centuries in both the Islamic world and [Europe](/Europe). [Rhazes](/Rhazes) was the first to identify [smallpox](/Smallpox) and [measles](/Measles). [Public hospitals](/Public_hospital) issued the first medical diplomas for licensed physicians. [187][188][189] [Ibn al-Haytham](/Ibn_al-Haytham) is regarded as the progenitor of the modern [scientific method](/Scientific_method) and is often hailed as the "world's first true scientist," particularly for his groundbreaking work in [optics]. [190][191][192] In engineering, the [Banū Mūsā](/Ban%C5%AB_M%C5%ABs%C4%81) brothers' [automaton](/Automaton), a mechanical flute player, is considered the first [programmable machine](/Program_(machine)). [193] The concept of the [algorithm](/Algorithm) in [mathematics](/Islamic_mathematics) is named after [Muhammad ibn Musa al-Khwarizmi](/Muhammad_ibn_Musa_al-Khwarizmi), who is also recognized as a founder of [algebra](/Algebra), derived from his book *al-jabr*. Other mathematicians developed the concept of a [function (mathematics)](/Function_(mathematics)). [194] Scientists received salaries equivalent to those of professional athletes today. [195] The [University of Al Karaouine](/University_of_Al_Karaouine), founded in 859 CE, is recognized by [Guinness World Records](/Guinness_World_Records) as the world's oldest degree-granting university. [196] Many non-Muslims, including [Christians](/Christians), [Jews](/Jews), and [Sabians](/Sabians), [197] significantly contributed to Islamic civilization across various disciplines. [198][199] The institution known as the [House of Wisdom](/House_of_Wisdom) employed [Christian](/List_of_Christian_scientists_and_scholars_of_the_medieval_Islamic_world) and [Persian scholars](/List_of_pre-modern_Iranian_scientists_and_scholars) for translation work and the advancement of knowledge. [200][197][201]

Autonomous regions broke away from the Abbasid empire, establishing their own dynasties, such as the [Tulunids](/Tulunid) in Egypt in 868 CE [202] and the [Ghaznavid dynasty](/Ghaznavid) in Central Asia in 977 CE. [203] This era of fragmentation coincided with the "[Shi'a Century](/Shi%27a_Century)," approximately from 945 to 1055 CE, marked by the rise of the [millennialist](/Millennialist) [Isma'ili](/Isma%27ili) Shia missionary movement. The [Fatimid dynasty](/Fatimid_dynasty), an Isma'ili group, gained control of North Africa in the 10th century, [204] while the [Qarmatians](/Qarmatians), another Isma'ili faction, sacked Mecca and stole the [Black Stone](/Black_Stone), a sacred object within the Kaaba, during their unsuccessful rebellion. [205] The [Buyid dynasty](/Buyid_dynasty), also Isma'ili, conquered Baghdad, reducing the Abbasid Caliphate to a symbolic monarchy. The Sunni Seljuk dynasty sought to re-establish Sunni Islam by promoting scholarly consensus, notably through the establishment of educational institutions called [Nezamiyeh](/Nezamiyeh), associated with figures like Al-Ghazali and [Saadi Shirazi]. [206]

The expansion of the Muslim world included the conversion of [Volga Bulgaria](/Volga_Bulgaria) to Islam through missionary efforts. The [Delhi Sultanate](/Delhi_Sultanate) extended its influence deep into the [Indian subcontinent](/Indian_subcontinent), leading to numerous conversions to Islam, particularly among [low-caste Hindus](/Dalit), whose descendants now form the majority of Indian Muslims. [207][208] Trade routes facilitated the presence of Muslims in [China](/Islam_in_China), where they dominated the import and export sector during the [Song dynasty](/Song_dynasty). [209] Muslims were integrated as a [governing minority class](/Semu) within the [Yuan dynasty](/Yuan_dynasty). [210]

#### Pre-modern Era (1258–18th Century)

##### Safavid Conversion of Iran to Shia Islam

Through extensive Muslim trade networks and the activities of Sufi orders, [211] Islam disseminated into new regions [212] and Muslim populations integrated into diverse cultures.

The [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire) facilitated the spread of Islam into [Southeast Europe](/Southeast_Europe). [213] Conversion to Islam often involved degrees of [syncretism](/Syncretism), [214] as evidenced by Muhammad's appearance in [Hindu](/Hinduism) folklore. [215] Muslim Turks incorporated elements of [Turkish Shamanism beliefs](/Tengrism) into their practice of Islam. [c][217] During the Ming Dynasty in China, Muslims of earlier immigrant descent assimilated culturally, sometimes through mandated assimilation policies, [218] adopting Chinese names and customs, with [Nanjing](/Nanjing) becoming a significant center for Islamic scholarship. [219][220]

Cultural shifts became apparent with a diminished Arab influence following the [Mongol destruction](/Mongol_invasions_and_conquests) of the Abbasid Caliphate. [221] The Muslim Mongol Khanates in [Iran](/Ilkhanate) and [Central Asia](/Chagatai_Khanate) benefited from increased cross-cultural exchange with East Asia under [Mongol rule](/Pax_Mongolica), fostering distinct cultural developments separate from Arab influence, such as the [Timurid Renaissance](/Timurid_Renaissance) under the [Timurid dynasty](/Timurid_dynasty). [222] [Nasir al-Din al-Tusi](/Nasir_al-Din_al-Tusi) (1201–1274) proposed the [Tusi couple](/Tusi_couple), a mathematical model later suggested to have been adopted by [Copernicus](/Copernicus) without revision in his [heliocentric](/Heliocentrism) model. [223] [Jamshīd al-Kāshī](/Jamsh%C4%ABd_al-K%C4%81sh%C4%AB)'s calculation of [pi](/Pi) remained unsurpassed for 180 years. [224]

Following the introduction of gunpowder weaponry, large, centralized Muslim states consolidated around what are known as [gunpowder empires], diverging from the previous fragmentation across various territories. The [Ottoman dynasty](/Ottoman_dynasty) of the Ottoman Empire claimed the title of [caliphate](/Ottoman_Caliphate), solidifying its claims in 1517 when [Selim I](/Selim_I) assumed control of Mecca and Medina. [225] The Shia [Safavid dynasty](/Safavid_dynasty) rose to power in 1501, subsequently conquering all of Iran. [226] In South Asia, [Babur](/Babur) founded the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire). [227]

The state religions of these centralized gunpowder empires significantly influenced the religious practices of their populations. A symbiotic relationship between [Ottoman rulers](/List_of_sultans_of_the_Ottoman_Empire) and Sufism deeply impacted Ottoman governance from its inception. Orders like the [Mevlevi Order](/Mevlevi_Order) and the [Bektashis](/Bektashis) maintained close ties with the sultans, [228] fostering the flourishing of both mystical Sufi practices and [heterodox](/Heterodox) and [syncretic](/Syncretic) approaches to Islam. The often forceful [Safavid conversion of Iran](/Safavid_conversion_of_Iran_to_Shia_Islam) to the Twelver Shia Islam of the Safavid Empire ensured the eventual dominance of the [Twelver sect](/Twelver) within Shia Islam. Persian migrants to South Asia, acting as influential administrators and landowners, contributed to the spread of Shia Islam, establishing significant Shia communities outside of Iran. [229] [Nader Shah](/Nader_Shah), who deposed the Safavids, attempted to improve relations with Sunnis by proposing the integration of Twelverism into Sunni Islam as a fifth *madhhab*, known as Ja'farism, [230] but this initiative failed to gain recognition from the Ottomans. [231][232]

#### Modern Era (18th–20th Centuries)

[Abdülmecid II](/Abd%C3%BClmecid_II), the last Caliph of the [Ottoman dynasty](/Ottoman_dynasty).

In the 14th century, [Ibn Taymiyya](/Ibn_Taymiyya) championed a [puritanical](/Puritan) interpretation of Islam, [233] advocating for a return to simpler theology over philosophical abstractions [233] and calling for the reopening of the gates of [ijtihad](/Ijtihad) rather than adhering to blind imitation of scholars. [234] He also advocated for *jihad* against those he deemed heretical, [235] though his writings had a limited impact during his lifetime. [236] In 18th-century Arabia, [Muhammad ibn 'Abd al-Wahhab](/Muhammad_ibn_Abd_al-Wahhab), influenced by Ibn Taymiyya and [Ibn al-Qayyim](/Ibn_al-Qayyim), founded a movement known as [Wahhabism](/Wahhabi) to restore what he perceived as unadulterated Islam. [237][238] He condemned many local Islamic customs, such as venerating the tomb of Muhammad or saints, as later [innovations](/Bidah) and sinful practices. [238][239] He ordered the destruction of sacred rocks and trees, Sufi shrines, the [tombs of Muhammad and his companions](/Destruction_of_early_Islamic_heritage_sites_in_Saudi_Arabia), and the tomb of Husayn in Karbala, a major Shia pilgrimage site. [239][240][241] He formed an alliance with the [Saud family](/House_of_Saud), which eventually led to their conquest of the territory that would become [Saudi Arabia](/Saudi_Arabia) by the 1920s. [239][242] In China, movements like [Sailaifengye](/Sailaifengye), promoted by [Ma Wanfu](/Ma_Wanfu) and Ma Debao in the 19th century after their return from Mecca, were eventually suppressed by Sufi groups, forcing their adherents into hiding. [243] Other reform movements sought to revise Sufism rather than reject it; the [Senusiyya](/Senusiyya) and [Muhammad Ahmad](/Muhammad_Ahmad) waged wars and established states in Libya and Sudan, respectively. [244][page needed] In India, [Shah Waliullah Dehlawi](/Shah_Waliullah_Dehlawi) adopted a more conciliatory approach toward Sufism, influencing the [Deobandi](/Deobandi) movement. [245] In response, the [Barelwi](/Barelwi) movement emerged as a popular counter-movement, defending traditional Sufism and advocating for its reform. [246][247]

The [Muslim world](/Muslim_world) experienced a general political decline from the 1800s onwards, particularly in comparison to European powers. Earlier, in the 15th century, the [Reconquista](/Reconquista) successfully ended the [Muslim presence in Iberia](/Taifa). By the 19th century, the British [East India Company](/Company_rule_in_India) had formally annexed the [Mughal dynasty](/Mughal_dynasty) in India. [248] In response to [Western Imperialism](/Imperialism), many intellectuals initiated movements for [Islamic reform](/Islamic_revival). [249] [Islamic modernism](/Islamic_modernism), initially termed Salafiyya by Western scholars, embraced modern values and institutions like [democracy while maintaining scriptural adherence](/Islam_and_democracy). Key figures in this movement included [Muhammad 'Abduh](/Muhammad_Abduh) and [Jamal al-Din al-Afghani](/Jamal_al-Din_al-Afghani). [250] [Abul A'la Maududi](/Abul_A%27la_Maududi) significantly influenced modern [political Islam](/Political_Islam). [251][252] For the first time, elements of Sharia were partially codified into law in 1869 within the Ottoman Empire's [Mecelle](/Mecelle) code, aligning with contemporary trends in legal [codification](/Civil_code). [253]

The [Ottoman Empire dissolved](/Fall_of_the_Ottoman_Empire) after [World War I](/World_War_I), and the [Ottoman Caliphate](/Ottoman_Caliphate) was [abolished in 1924](/Abolition_of_the_Caliphate). [254] The subsequent [Sharifian Caliphate](/Sharifian_Caliphate) quickly collapsed, [255][256][257] leaving Islam without a recognized [Caliph](/Caliphate). [257] [Pan-Islamists](/Pan-Islam) sought to unify Muslims, competing with emerging nationalist movements like [pan-Arabism](/Pan-Arabism). [258][259] The [Organisation of Islamic Cooperation](/Organisation_of_Islamic_Cooperation), comprising [Muslim-majority countries](/Islam_by_country), was established in 1969 following the arson of the [Al-Aqsa Mosque](/Qibli_Mosque) in [Jerusalem](/Jerusalem). [260]

The advent of global communication networks facilitated the widespread dissemination of religious knowledge. The adoption of the [hijab](/Hijab) has become more prevalent, [284] and some Muslim intellectuals are increasingly endeavoring to distinguish scriptural Islamic tenets from cultural traditions. [285] This increased access to information has also led to the rise of popular "[televangelist](/Televangelist)" preachers, such as [Amr Khaled](/Amr_Khaled), who rival the traditional [ulema](/Ulema) in their reach, thereby decentralizing religious authority. [286][287] More "individualized" interpretations of Islam [288] are notably espoused by [Liberal Muslims](/Liberal_Muslims), who aim to reconcile religious traditions with contemporary secular governance, [289][290] an approach that has drawn criticism regarding its compatibility with traditional interpretations. [291][292] Furthermore, secularism is often perceived as an alien ideology imposed by external forces and perpetuated by post-colonial [ruling elites](/Ruling_class), frequently equated with [anti-religion]. [293][294]

## Demographics

### Muslim World and Ummah

### Islam by Country and Muslim Population Growth

As of 2020, approximately 25.6% of the global population, or roughly 2 billion individuals, identify as Muslim. [13][296][297][298][299][300] This figure stood at 12.3% in 1900 [301] and 19.9% in 1990, [263] with projections indicating it will reach 29.7% by 2050. [295]:8 A 2020 Pew study identified the global Muslim population as the fastest-growing religious group over the preceding decade, primarily attributed to a younger average age and higher birth rates among Muslims, factors that significantly drive natural population increase. [302]:9

Pew Research estimates that 87–90% of Muslims are Sunni and 10–13% are Shia. [303] Approximately 49 countries are [Muslim-majority](/List_of_Muslim_majority_countries), [304][305][306][307][308] with 62% of the world's Muslims residing in Asia. Indonesia alone accounts for 683 million adherents, [309] alongside significant populations in [Pakistan](/Islam_in_Pakistan), [India](/Islam_in_India), and [Bangladesh](/Islam_in_Bangladesh). [310][311][312] Arab Muslims constitute the largest ethnic group among Muslims globally, [313] followed by Bengalis [314][315] and Punjabis. [316] Estimates suggest China has between 20 to 30 million Muslims (1.5% to 2% of its population). [317][318] [Islam in Europe](/Islam_in_Europe) is the second-largest religion after [Christianity](/Christianity) in many European nations, with growth driven primarily by immigration and higher birth rates among Muslims. In 2016, Muslims represented 4.9% of Europe's total population. [319][320]

Religious conversion has a negligible net impact on global Muslim population growth, as the number of individuals converting to Islam appears to be roughly balanced by the number of Muslims leaving the faith. [321] However, Islam is projected to experience a modest net gain of 3 million converts between 2010 and 2050, predominantly from [Sub-Saharan Africa](/Sub_Saharan_Africa) (2.9 million). [322][323] A 2020 Pew study indicated that approximately 1% of adults raised Muslim leave the faith, with a similar proportion (around 1%) converting to Islam from other religions, resulting in low rates of religious switching in both directions. [324] [Ex-Muslims](/Ex-Muslims) are more likely to convert to another religion than to become unaffiliated. [13]

According to a [CNN](/CNN) report, Islam attracts converts from all backgrounds, with a notable influx from African-Americans. [325] In [Britain](/Islam_in_Britain), an estimated 6,000 individuals convert to Islam annually, with women constituting the majority of new converts. [326] The Huffington Post reports that observers estimate up to 20,000 Americans convert to Islam each year, with women and African-Americans forming the largest demographic groups. [327][328]

Islam is the world's fastest-growing major religious group by both percentage and absolute numbers, and is projected to surpass [Christianity](/Christianity) as the largest religion by the end of the 21st century. [329][295] By 2050, the Muslim population is expected to nearly equal the Christian population globally, largely due to the younger age structure and higher [fertility rate](/Fertility_rate) among Muslims compared to other religious groups. [295]:70

## Main Branches or Denominations

### Sunni Islam

#### Sunni Islam

Sunni Islam, or Sunnism, represents the largest denomination within Islam. [330][331][332] The term derives from "Ahl as-Sunnah wa'l-Jama'ah," meaning "people of the [Sunnah] (Muhammad's traditions) and the community." [333] While sometimes referred to as "orthodox Islam," [334][335][336] this designation is debated, and may be considered offensive by non-Sunnis. [337] Sunnis believe the first four Caliphs were Muhammad's rightful successors and primarily consult the [six major hadith works](/Al-Kutub_Al-Sittah) for legal matters, adhering to one of the four main schools of jurisprudence: Hanafi, Hanbali, Maliki, or Shafi'i. [338][339]

[Traditionalist theology](/Traditionalist_theology_(Islam)), prominently advocated by [Ahmad ibn Hanbal](/Ahmad_ibn_Hanbal) (780–855 CE), emphasizes a [textualist](/Textualism) interpretation of the Quran and Sunnah, views the Quran as uncreated and eternal, and opposes speculative theology (*[kalam](/Kalam)*) in religious and ethical matters. [340] [Maturidism](/Maturidism), founded by [Abu Mansur al-Maturidi](/Abu_Mansur_al-Maturidi) (853–944 CE), posits that basic ethics can be understood through reason alone, though revelation is necessary for matters beyond human comprehension. [341] [Ash'arism](/Ash%27arism), established by [Al-Ashʿarī](/Al-Ash%CA%BFar%C4%AB) (c. 874–936 CE), suggests that ethics can be derived from divine revelation but accepts reason for interpretative purposes, blending Muʿtazila approaches with traditionalist ideas. [342]

[Salafism](/Salafism) is a revivalist movement advocating a return to the practices of the earliest generations of Muslims. Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab led a prominent [Salafi movement](/Salafi_movement), often termed Wahhabism by outsiders, in present-day Saudi Arabia during the 18th century. [343] A similar movement, [Ahl al-Hadith](/Ahl_al-Hadith), also de-emphasized traditional Sunni legal interpretations, favoring direct adherence to the Quran and Hadith. The [Nurcu](/Nur_movement) Sunni movement, initiated by [Said Nursi](/Said_Nursi) (1877–1960), incorporates elements of Sufism and science. [344][345]

#### Shia Islam

##### Shia Islam

[Nahj al-Balagha](/Nahj_al-balagha), a compilation of sermons, letters, and sayings attributed to [Imam Ali](/Ali).

Shia Islam, or Shi'ism, is the second-largest Muslim denomination. [346][347][303] Shia Muslims maintain that Muhammad's rightful successor as leader must be a descendant from his family, known as the [Ahl al-Bayt](/Ahl_al-Bayt). These leaders, designated as [Imams](/Imamate_in_Shia_doctrine), are believed to possess additional spiritual authority. [348][349] Shias follow the [Ja'fari school of jurisprudence](/Ja%27fari_school). [350]

Both Sunni and Shia Muslims recount a significant event at [Ghadir Khumm](/Ghadir_Khumm) during Muhammad's return from his final pilgrimage, where he addressed thousands of Muslims. [351] Muhammad reportedly appointed his cousin [Ali](/Ali) as the executor of his will and his *Wali* (guardian/authority). [352][353] Shia Muslims assert that Muhammad designated Ali as his successor (*khalifa*) and [Imam](/Imamate_in_Shia_doctrine) (spiritual and political leader) after him, but that Ali was prevented from succeeding Muhammad due to the actions of certain [companions](/Companions_of_the_Prophet) who selected [Abu Bakr](/Abu_Bakr) as [caliph](/Caliphate). [354] Sunnis, conversely, believe Muhammad did not appoint a successor before his death and consider Abu Bakr to be the first rightful caliph. [355] Shia Muslims contend that Ali's nomination was deliberately overlooked, [356] citing Umar's appointment by Abu Bakr [357] and other historical accounts, [358] as well as the Quran's emphasis on legitimacy not being determined by majority opinion. [359]

Several early Shia Imams, including Ali and [Husayn](/Husayn_ibn_Ali), are revered by both Sunni and Shia Muslims. [360] [Twelvers](/Twelvers), the largest Shia branch, believe in [Twelve Imams](/Twelve_Imams), the last of whom is believed to be in [occultation](/Occultation_(Islam)) and will return. They recognize that the prophecy of the Twelve Imams is foretold in the [Hadith of the Twelve Successors](/Hadith_of_the_Twelve_Successors), recorded in both Sunni and Shia sources. [361] [Zaydism](/Zaydism) rejects the infallibility of Imams and has sometimes been considered a 'fifth school' of Sunni Islam rather than a Shia denomination, [362][363] differing from other Shia groups regarding the status of the fifth Imam. They are sometimes known as "Fivers". [364] The [Isma'ilis](/Ismailism) diverged from the Twelvers over the succession of the seventh Imam and have subsequently fragmented into various groups based on the status of subsequent Imams, with the Nizaris being the largest faction. [365]

For Shia Muslims, the [Imam Ali Shrine](/Imam_Ali_Shrine) in Najaf, the [Imam Husayn Shrine](/Imam_Husayn_Shrine) in Karbala, and the [Fatima Masumeh Shrine](/Fatima_Masumeh_Shrine) in [Qom](/Qom) are also considered among the [Islamic Holy Sites](/Holiest_sites_in_Islam). [366]

#### Muhakkima

##### Muhakkima, Ibadi Islam, and Kharijites

[Ibadism](/Ibadism) represents the third-largest branch of Islam, with origins tracing back to the [Kharijite](/Kharijites) secession from the fourth Caliph, Ali. [367] It is practiced by approximately 1.45 million Muslims globally (about 0.08% of all Muslims), primarily in [Oman]. [368] Ibadism is often associated with and viewed as a moderate variant of Kharijism, though Ibadis themselves reject this classification. The Kharijites were groups that rebelled against Caliph Ali for accepting arbitration with an individual they deemed a sinner. Unlike most Kharijite groups, Ibadism does not consider Muslims who commit grave sins to be unbelievers. Ibadi hadith collections, such as the [Jami Sahih](/Jami_Sahih), utilize chains of narrators from early Islamic history considered trustworthy; however, most Ibadi hadith are also found in standard Sunni collections, and contemporary Ibadis often accept these standard Sunni compilations. [369]

An overview of the major sects and madhahib of Islam.

#### Other Denominations

*   The [Ahmadiyya Movement](/Ahmadiyya_Movement) was founded in British India in 1889 by [Mirza Ghulam Ahmad](/Mirza_Ghulam_Ahmad) of [Qadian]. He claimed to be the prophesied [Messiah](/Messiah) ("[Second Coming](/Second_Coming) of [Christ](/Jesus_in_Islam)"), the [Mahdi](/Mahdi) awaited by Muslims, and a "[subordinate" prophet](/Prophethood_(Ahmadiyya)) to Muhammad. [370][371] Ahmadis hold distinct beliefs and teachings compared to most other Muslims, [370][372][373][371] including differing interpretations of the Quranic title [Khatam an-Nabiyyin](/Khatam_an-Nabiyyin) and the concept of the [Messiah's Second Coming](/Jesus_in_Ahmadiyya_Islam). [372][375] These perceived deviations from normative Islamic thought have led to their rejection by the majority of Muslims as heretics, [376] resulting in the [persecution of Ahmadis](/Persecution_of_Ahmadis) in various countries, [372] particularly [Pakistan](/Ahmadiyya_in_Pakistan), [372][377] where the [Government of Pakistan](/Government_of_Pakistan) officially declared them non-Muslims. [378] The Ahmadiyya Movement is divided into two main groups: the [Ahmadiyya Muslim Community](/Ahmadiyya_Muslim_Community), currently the dominant faction, and the [Lahore Ahmadiyya Movement for the Propagation of Islam]. [372]

*   [Alevism](/Alevism) is a [syncretic](/Syncretism) and [heterodox](/Heterodoxy) indigenous Islamic tradition whose adherents follow the mystical (*bāṭenī*, [Batin_(Islam)]) teachings of Ali and [Haji Bektash Veli](/Haji_Bektash_Veli). [379] Alevism integrates traditional 14th-century Turkish beliefs, [380] possibly with syncretic influences from [Shamanism](/Tengrism) and [Animism](/Animism), alongside Shia and Sufi doctrines. Estimates place the global Alevi population between 10 million and over 20 million (approximately 0.5–1% of all Muslims). [381]

*   [Quranism](/Quranism) is a religious movement within Islam founded on the principle that Islamic law and guidance should derive solely from the [Quran](/Quran), excluding the [Sunnah](/Sunnah) or [Hadith](/Hadith). [382] Quranists exhibit notable differences in their approach to the [five pillars of Islam](/Five_pillars_of_Islam). [383] The movement emerged in the 19th century with thinkers like [Syed Ahmad Khan](/Syed_Ahmad_Khan), Abdullah Chakralawi, and [Ghulam Ahmed Perwez](/Ghulam_Ahmed_Perwez) in India questioning the authority of the hadith tradition. [384] In Egypt, [Muhammad Tawfiq Sidqi](/Muhammad_Tawfiq_Sidqi) published the article "Islam is the Quran alone" in the magazine [Al-Manār](/Al-Man%C4%81r_(magazine)), advocating for the Quran's exclusive authority. [385] A prominent late 20th-century Quranist was [Rashad Khalifa](/Rashad_Khalifa), an Egyptian-American biochemist who claimed to have discovered a [numerological](/Numerology) [code in the Quran](/Quran_code) and founded the Quranist organization [United Submitters International](/United_Submitters_International). [386]

*   [Mu'tazilism](/Mu%27tazilism) was an early Islamic theological school distinguished by its emphasis on [rationalism](/Rationalism), particularly in interpreting the Quran and the hadith. [387][388] The school was founded on five core principles: divine oneness (*[tawhid](/Tawhid)*), divine justice, the certainty of divine promises and threats, an intermediate position regarding the status of major sinners, and the obligation to promote good and forbid evil. [388] Unlike Sunnis, Mu'tazilites rejected the traditional view of the Quran as God's uncreated word, asserting instead that the [Quran was a created revelation](/Quranic_createdness) to uphold God's absolute oneness. [389] Emphasizing reason, they argued that human [free will](/Free_will) enabled individuals to choose between good and evil, making them accountable for their actions. [390] Although Mu'tazilism's influence declined due to socio-political pressures from orthodox Sunnis, its rationalist legacy remains significant in [Islamic intellectualism](/Islamic_modernity). [391][392]

#### Non-denominational Muslims

##### Non-denominational Muslim

The term "Non-denominational Muslims" serves as an [umbrella term](/Umbrella_term) for Muslims who do not affiliate with or self-identify as belonging to a specific [Islamic denomination](/Islamic_denomination). [393][394] Recent surveys indicate that a substantial proportion of Muslims in certain regions identify as "just Muslim," although detailed analysis of the motivations behind this response is limited. [395][396][397] Pew Research reports that individuals identifying as "just Muslim" constitute a majority in seven countries and a plurality in three others, with the highest percentage recorded in [Kazakhstan](/Kazakhstan) at 74%. At least one in five Muslims in 22 countries self-identifies in this manner. [398]

## Mysticism

### Sufism

#### Sufism

[Sufism](/Sufism), known in Arabic as *tasawwuf* (تصوف), is a [mystical](/Mystical) and [ascetic](/Ascetic) approach to Islam that seeks direct [personal experience of God](/Divine_presence). Classical Sufi scholars defined *tasawwuf* as "a science whose objective is the reparation of the heart and turning it away from all else but God," achieved through "intuitive and emotional faculties" requiring dedicated training. [399][400][401][402] [Ahmad ibn Ajiba](/Ahmad_ibn_Ajiba) described *tasawwuf* as "a return to the tradition, and its beginning is knowledge, its middle is action [upon that knowledge], and its end is a gift [from Allah]." [403] Sufism is not a sect but rather a dimension of Islam, with its adherents belonging to various Muslim denominations. [Isma'ilism](/Isma%27ilism), with teachings rooted in [Gnosticism](/Gnosticism) and [Neoplatonism](/Neoplatonism), [404] as well as influenced by the [Illuminationist](/Illuminationism) and [Isfahan](/School_of_Isfahan) schools of Islamic philosophy, has developed its own mystical interpretations of Islam. [405] Early Sufis like [Hasan al-Basri](/Hasan_al-Basri) emphasized fear of divine judgment for disobedience. In contrast, later prominent Sufis, such as [Mansur Al-Hallaj](/Mansur_Al-Hallaj) and [Jalaluddin Rumi](/Rumi), stressed religiosity based on divine love. Rumi's devotional poetry continues to be highly popular, making him one of America's bestselling poets. [407][408]

Sufis view *tasawwuf* as an integral aspect of Islam. [409] Traditional Sufis, including [Bayazid Bastami](/Bayazid_Bastami), Jalaluddin Rumi, [Haji Bektash Veli](/Haji_Bektash_Veli), [Junaid Baghdadi](/Junaid_Baghdadi), and Al-Ghazali, argued that Sufism is grounded in Islamic tenets and the teachings of the Prophet. [410][409] Historian [Nile Green](/Nile_Green) suggests that Islam in the medieval period was largely synonymous with Sufism. [411] Adherents of the Sunni [revivalist](/Islamic_revival) movement known as [Salafism](/Salafism) consider popular devotional practices, such as the veneration of Sufi saints, to be innovations deviating from original Islam. Salafist actions have sometimes included physical attacks on Sufis, contributing to strained [Sufi–Salafi relations](/Sufi%E2%80%93Salafi_relations). [412]

Sufi congregations organize into orders (*[tariqa](/Tariqa)*), centered around a teacher (*[wali](/Wali)*) who traces a spiritual lineage back to Muhammad. [413] Sufis played a significant role in shaping Muslim societies through their missionary and educational endeavors. [169] The Sufi-influenced Ahle Sunnat movement, or [Barelvi](/Barelvi) movement, claims over 200 million followers in South Asia. [414][415][416] Sufism is prominent in Central Asia, [417][418] and in African nations such as [Tunisia](/Tunisia), [Algeria](/Algeria), [Morocco](/Morocco), [Senegal](/Senegal), [Chad], and [Niger]. [398][419]

## Law and Jurisprudence

### Sharia and Fiqh

#### Logic in Islamic Philosophy § Islamic Law and Theology

Islamic [schools of law](/Madhhab) across the [Muslim world](/Muslim_world) [citation needed].

[Sharia](/Shariah) constitutes the body of Islamic [religious law]. [338][420] The pursuit of a comprehensive and consistent methodology for discerning and applying these laws led to the development of legal theory, known as [fiqh](/Fiqh). [421][411] Conversely, [bid'ah](/Bid%27ah) refers to unlawful innovations within religious practice. [423] Different interpretive methodologies, termed principles of fiqh or [Usul al-fiqh](/Usul_al-fiqh), have evolved, with a school of jurisprudence that emerges around a particular methodology being known as a *madhhab* (مذهب). Adherence to the decisions of a legal expert or school is called [taqlid](/Taqlid). The term [ghair muqallid](/Salafi_movement) describes those who do not practice *taqlid* and, consequently, do not belong to a *madhhab*. [424] The exercise of independent reasoning in interpreting Sharia is termed [ijtihad](/Ijtihad). [425][426] Those who interpret Sharia are designated as [muftis](/Mufti), and their legal pronouncements are known as [fatwas](/Fatwa). [426][422]

The primary sources of Sharia are the Quran and the Sunnah. [427] A commonly accepted third source is [qiyas](/Qiyas) (analogical reasoning), employed for legal questions not explicitly addressed in the Quran or Sunnah. This involves identifying parallels to find the *illah*, or effective cause, which underpins an existing ruling. [428] For example, the prohibition of wine is extended to all alcohol based on the shared operative cause of mind-altering properties. [429][430] The [Zahiri school](/Zahiri_school) adheres to strict literalism and therefore rejects *qiyas*. Scholarly consensus is referred to as [ijma](/Ijma), while scholarly disagreement is known as [ikhtilaf](/Ikhtilaf). Legal rulings categorize actions into five classifications, or [ahkam](/Ahkam): mandatory (*fard*), recommended (*mustahabb*), permissible (*mubah*), discouraged (*makruh*), and prohibited (*haram*). [426][422]

In the modern era, Sharia-based criminal laws were largely supplanted by statutes influenced by European legal models. [422] The [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire)'s 19th-century [Tanzimat](/Tanzimat) reforms introduced the [Mecelle](/Mecelle) civil code, marking the initial attempt to [codify](/Codification_(law)) Sharia. [253] While the constitutions of most Muslim-majority nations reference Sharia, its classical regulations are primarily retained within [personal status](/Status_(law)) (family) laws. [422] Legislative bodies responsible for codifying these laws sought to modernize them while preserving their foundational principles within traditional jurisprudence. [422][431] The [Islamic revival](/Islamic_revival) of the late 20th century witnessed renewed calls from [Islamist](/Islamist) movements for the full implementation of Sharia. [422][431] The role of Sharia remains a contentious issue globally, with ongoing debates concerning its compatibility with secular governance, human rights, [freedom of thought](/Freedom_of_thought), and [women's rights], particularly regarding concerns about [censorship](/Religious_censorship) and [violence](/Islam_and_violence). [432][433]

## Society

### Religious Personages

#### Ulama

[Crimean Tatar](/Crimean_Tatars) Muslim students (1856).

Islam lacks a sacerdotal clergy comparable to priests who mediate between God and individuals. [434] The title of [Imam](/Imam) (إمام) denotes a leadership position within Islamic practice, often associated with conducting congregational worship. Religious interpretation is primarily guided by the *ʿulamāʾ* (علماء), a collective term for Muslim scholars trained in [Islamic studies](/Islamic_studies). A scholar specializing in hadith is a [muhaddith](/Muhaddith), a jurisprudence scholar is a [faqih](/Faqih) (فقيه), a jurist qualified to issue legal opinions (*[fatwas](/Fatwas)*) is a [mufti](/Mufti), and an Islamic judge is a [qadi](/Qadi). Scholars may also receive honorific titles such as [sheikh](/Sheikh), [mullah](/Mullah), or [mawlawi](/Mawlawi_(Islamic_title)). Some Muslims also venerate [saints](/Saints_in_Islam) associated with [miracles](/Islamic_view_of_miracles) (*karāmāt*, كرامات). [435]

### Governance

#### Political Aspects of Islam, Islamic Economics, Islamic Military Jurisprudence, Tasamuh, and Jihad

In [Islamic economic jurisprudence](/Islamic_economic_jurisprudence), hoarding of wealth is condemned, and [monopolistic](/Monopoly) practices are discouraged. [436] Efforts to adhere to Sharia have led to the development of [Islamic banking](/Islamic_banking). Islam prohibits *[riba](/Riba)*, commonly translated as [usury](/Usury), which encompasses any unfair gain in trade and is most often understood as [interest](/Interest). [437] Instead, Islamic banks engage in profit-and-loss sharing partnerships with borrowers. Another principle is the avoidance of excessive uncertainty, considered akin to gambling, [438] leading Islamic banks to typically eschew derivative instruments like futures or options, which has historically offered protection against market volatility. [439] The Rashidun and Umayyad Caliphates managed charitable distribution from the treasury, known as [Bayt al-mal](/Bayt_al-mal), before this function became largely individualized around 720 CE. The first Caliph, [Abu Bakr](/Abu_Bakr), distributed *zakat*, an early example of a [guaranteed minimum income](/Guaranteed_minimum_income), providing each citizen with 10 to 20 [dirhams](/Dirhams) annually. [440] During the reign of the second Caliph, Umar, [child support](/Child_support) was introduced, and stipends were provided for the elderly and disabled. [441][442] Caliph [Umar II](/Umar_II) assigned a servant for each blind individual and for every two chronically ill persons. [443]

*[Jihad](/Jihad) translates to "to strive or struggle [in the way of God]" and, in its broadest sense, means "to exert one's utmost power, efforts, endeavors, or ability in contending with an object of disapprobation." [444] Shia Muslims, in particular, emphasize the "greater jihad" of striving for spiritual [self-perfection], [445][446][447] while the "lesser jihad" is defined as warfare. [448][449] When used without qualification, jihad often refers to its military dimension. [444][445] Jihad is the sole form of warfare permitted under Islamic law and can be waged against unlawful acts, terrorists, criminal organizations, rebels, [apostates](/Apostasy_in_Islam), and oppressive leaders or states. [448][449] Most contemporary Muslims interpret jihad as exclusively defensive warfare. [450] Jihad becomes an individual obligation only for those in positions of authority; for the general populace, it is a duty only during a state of [general mobilization]. [449] For most [Twelver Shias](/Twelver), [offensive jihad](/Offensive_jihad) can only be declared by a [divinely appointed leader](/Imamate_in_Twelver_doctrine) of the Muslim community and is therefore suspended since the [occultation](/Occultation_(Islam)) of [Muhammad al-Mahdi](/Muhammad_al-Mahdi) in 868 CE. [451][452]

#### Daily and Family Life

##### Adab (Islam), Islamic Dietary Laws, Islam and Children, Marriage in Islam, Women in Islam, Polygyny in Islam

Many daily practices fall under the category of *adab*, or etiquette. Specific prohibited foods include pork products, blood, and [carrion](/Carrion). Health is considered a trust from God, and [intoxicants](/Khamr), such as [alcoholic drinks](/Alcoholic_drink), are forbidden. [453] All meat must originate from a [herbivorous](/Herbivorous) animal slaughtered in the name of God by a Muslim, Jew, or Christian; game hunted or fished by oneself is permissible. [454][455][456] Beards are often encouraged for men as a natural characteristic, [457] and body modifications, such as [permanent tattoos](/Religious_perspectives_on_tattooing), are generally prohibited as they alter God's creation. [d][459] Silk and gold are forbidden for men to maintain a state of sobriety. [460] *[Haya](/Haya_(Islam))*, often translated as "shame" or "modesty," is considered an inherent trait in Islam [461] and influences much of daily Muslim life. [Islamic clothing](/Islamic_clothing) emphasizes modesty, including the [hijab](/Hijab) for women. Similarly, [personal hygiene](/Islamic_hygienical_jurisprudence) is encouraged with specific requirements. [462]

A Muslim couple.

In [Islamic marriage](/Marriage_in_Islam), the groom is obligated to provide a bridal gift (*[mahr](/Mahr)*). [463][464][465] The majority of families in the Islamic world are monogamous. [466][467] Muslim men are permitted to practice [polygyny](/Polygyny), having up to four wives simultaneously. Islamic teachings strongly advise that if a man cannot ensure equal financial and emotional support for each wife, he should marry only one. One justification offered for polygyny is that it provides financial security for multiple women who might otherwise lack support (e.g., widows). However, the first wife can stipulate in the [marriage contract](/Marriage_in_Islam) that her husband may not marry another woman during their marriage. [468][469] Wedding customs also vary culturally. [470] [Polyandry](/Polyandry), the practice of a woman having two or more husbands, is prohibited in Islam. [471]

Muslim girls studying the [Quran](/Quran) on folding [lecterns](/Lectern) (*rehal*) during [Ramadan](/Ramadan) in [Qom](/Qom), [Iran](/Iran).

Following a child's birth, the [adhan](/Adhan) is recited in the right ear. [472] On the seventh day, the *[aqiqah](/Aqiqah)* ceremony is performed, involving the sacrifice of an animal whose meat is distributed among the poor. [473] The child's head is shaved, and an amount of money equivalent to the hair's weight is donated to the needy. [473] Male [circumcision](/Circumcision), known as *[khitan](/Khitan_(circumcision))*, [474] is a common practice in the Muslim world. [475][476] Respecting and obeying parents, and caring for them, especially in their old age, is a religious obligation. [477]

A [dying Muslim](/Islamic_view_of_death) is encouraged to recite the Shahada as their final words. [478] Honoring the deceased and participating in community funerals are considered virtuous acts. In [Islamic burial rituals](/Islamic_funeral), burial is expedited, usually within 24 hours. The body is washed by members of the same gender (except for martyrs) and enshrouded in simple white cloth (*kafan*). [479] A funeral prayer, known as [Salat al-Janazah](/Salat_al-Janazah), is performed. Loud wailing or excessive mourning is discouraged. Coffins are often not used, and graves are typically left unmarked, even for rulers. [480]

## Arts and Culture

### Islamic Culture

#### Islamic Art, Islamic Architecture, Islamic Literature, Islam in Association Football, and Cultural Muslims

The term "[Islamic culture](/Islamic_culture)" can refer to aspects of culture intrinsically linked to the religion, such as [festivals](/Festivals) and [dress codes](/Islamic_clothing). It is also sometimes used, though controversially, to denote the cultural characteristics of people who traditionally identify as Muslim. [481] Additionally, "Islamic civilization" may encompass the synthesized cultural elements of the early Caliphates, including contributions from non-Muslims, sometimes termed "Islamicate." [482][483]

[Islamic art](/Islamic_art) encompasses a wide range of visual arts, including [architecture](/Islamic_architecture), [calligraphy](/Islamic_calligraphy), painting, and [ceramics]. [484][485] While the depiction of animate beings has often been discouraged due to prohibitions against idolatry ([Aniconism_in_Islam](/Aniconism_in_Islam)), this rule has been interpreted differently across various scholarly traditions and historical periods. This stricture helps explain the prominence of [calligraphy](/Islamic_calligraphy), [tessellation](/Tessellation), and intricate patterns as defining features of Islamic artistic expression. [486] Furthermore, the [depiction of Muhammad](/Depictions_of_Muhammad) remains a sensitive and debated issue among Muslims. [487] [Islamic architecture](/Islamic_architecture) exhibits diverse cultural influences; for instance, North African and Spanish Islamic architecture, such as the [Great Mosque of Kairouan](/Great_Mosque_of_Kairouan), incorporates columns of [marble](/Marble) and [porphyry](/Porphyry_(geology)) salvaged from Roman and Byzantine structures. [488] Conversely, [mosques in Indonesia](/Mosques_in_Indonesia) often feature multi-tiered roofs reflecting indigenous [Javanese](/Java) architectural styles. [489]

The [Islamic calendar](/Islamic_calendar) is a [lunar calendar](/Lunar_calendar) beginning with the [Hijra](/Hegira) of 622 CE, a date reportedly chosen by Caliph Umar as a significant turning point in Muhammad's life. [490] Islamic [holy days](/Muslim_holidays) follow fixed dates within this lunar calendar, meaning they occur in different [seasons](/Seasons) each year relative to the [Gregorian calendar](/Gregorian_calendar). The major Islamic festivals are [Eid al-Fitr](/Eid_al-Fitr) (عيد الفطر), celebrated on the 1st of [Shawwal](/Shawwal) to mark the end of Ramadan, and [Eid al-Adha](/Eid_al-Adha) (عيد الأضحى), observed on the 10th of Dhu al-Hijjah, coinciding with the conclusion of the [Hajj](/Hajj) pilgrimage. [491][94]

[Cultural Muslims](/Cultural_Muslims) are individuals who, while not actively practicing the religion, maintain an identification with Islam due to family background, personal experiences, or their social and cultural upbringing. [492][493]

